**`GameUI.tsx:129` — `power` in keydown effect dependency array**

This is the most impactful issue. When the power bar is charging, `power` updates ~60× per second. Because `power` is a dependency, the effect tears down and re-registers the `window` keydown listener 60× per second:

```tsx
// Current — listener removed/re-added every animation frame tick
useEffect(() => {
  const handleKeyDown = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
    ...
    onShoot(selectedDir, selectedHeight, Math.round(power), curve); // reads power
  };
  window.addEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown);
  return () => window.removeEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown);
}, [gameState, isCharging, selectedDir, selectedHeight, power, curve, onShoot]); // power here!
```

Fix: move `power` to a ref so the closure always reads the latest value without being a dep:

```tsx
const powerRef = useRef(power);
useEffect(() => { powerRef.current = power; }, [power]);

useEffect(() => {
  const handleKeyDown = (e: KeyboardEvent) => {
    if (e.code === 'Space' && !isCharging) {
      onShoot(selectedDir, selectedHeight, Math.round(powerRef.current), curve);
    }
  };
  window.addEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown);
  return () => window.removeEventListener('keydown', handleKeyDown);
}, [gameState, isCharging, selectedDir, selectedHeight, curve, onShoot]); // power removed
```

---

**`App.tsx:347` — inline `onAnimationTriggered` recreated every render**

```tsx
// Every render creates a new function reference
<StadiumCanvas onAnimationTriggered={() => {}} ... />
```

Since this is a no-op, just define it once:

```tsx
// App.tsx — outside component or as useCallback with []
const noop = useCallback(() => {}, []);
<StadiumCanvas onAnimationTriggered={noop} ... />
```

---

**`App.tsx:36` — `drawOpponent` recreated every render**

`drawOpponent` closes over `playerTeam` and `facedIds` but is never memoized. Wrap it:

```tsx
const drawOpponent = useCallback((): Team => {
  const pool = TEAMS.filter(t => t.id !== playerTeam.id && !facedIds.includes(t.id));
  const list = pool.length > 0 ? pool : TEAMS.filter(t => t.id !== playerTeam.id);
  return list[Math.floor(Math.random() * list.length)];
}, [playerTeam.id, facedIds]);
```

---

**`TeamSelector.tsx` — no memoization on a 48-button grid rendered twice**

`FlagBadge` renders 96 times on this screen (2 grids × 48 teams). It's a pure SVG lookup — a prime candidate for `React.memo`:

```tsx
// FlagBadge.tsx
export const FlagBadge = React.memo(function FlagBadge({ teamId, className }: FlagBadgeProps) {
  ...
});
```

The individual grid buttons in `TeamSelector` also get recreated on every state change (every selection). The two `TEAMS.map` loops produce new inline `onClick` handlers on every render. Extracting them into a memoized sub-component would prevent unnecessary work:

```tsx
const TeamButton = React.memo(({ team, idx, isSelected, onClick }: ...) => (
  <button onClick={() => onClick(idx)} ...>
    <FlagBadge teamId={team.id} ... />
  </button>
));
```

---

**`StadiumCanvas.tsx:765` — gradient objects created every frame**

```tsx
// Called every frame (~60fps) — allocates a new gradient object each time
const skyGrad = ctx.createLinearGradient(0, 0, 0, dimensions.height * 0.4);
```

Same applies to the 4 stadium light beam gradients at line ~860. These gradients don't change between frames (only on resize). Cache them outside the render loop:

```tsx
// Inside the useEffect, before render(), create once:
let skyGrad = ctx.createLinearGradient(0, 0, 0, dimensions.height * 0.4);
skyGrad.addColorStop(0, '#0f172a');
skyGrad.addColorStop(1, '#1e293b');
// reuse `skyGrad` inside render()
```

---

**`StadiumCanvas.tsx:724-743` — `document.getElementById` queried every frame**

During power-sweep phase (Step 2), the render loop calls `getElementById` twice per frame at 60fps:

```tsx
// Inside render(), called 60x/sec:
const fillEl = document.getElementById('power-bar-fill');
const textEl = document.getElementById('power-bar-text');
```

Cache these outside the render function (query once after first paint):

```tsx
// Inside useEffect, before render():
const fillEl = document.getElementById('power-bar-fill') as HTMLElement | null;
const textEl = document.getElementById('power-bar-text') as HTMLElement | null;
// render() uses fillEl/textEl from closure — no repeated lookups
```

---

**`StadiumCanvas.tsx:806-824` — crowd loop runs O(width × height) per frame with `Math.sin`**

The crowd renders `(width/18) × (crowdHeight/12)` pixels each frame (~1800 iterations at 1920px width). Each iteration calls `Math.sin` for color variation and jumping. The color variant (`rSeed`) is purely deterministic by position `(i, j)` — it never changes. Pre-compute an array of `{color, skinTone}` tuples once on resize:

```tsx
// Compute once (outside render, updated on resize):
type CrowdDot = { x: number; y: number; color: string };
const crowdDots: CrowdDot[] = [];
for (let i = 0; i < width; i += 18) {
  const rSeed = Math.sin(i * 100 + /* j * 50 - use base row */ 0);
  const color = rSeed > 0.45 ? '#ef4444' : rSeed > 0.1 ? '#3b82f6' : ...;
  crowdDots.push({ x: i, color });
}
// In render(): iterate crowdDots and only compute the per-frame `jump` sin
```

---

**`StadiumCanvas.tsx:586` — uncleaned `setTimeout` on resize**

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const handleResize = () => { ... setDimensions(...); };
  window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
  handleResize();
  setTimeout(handleResize, 100); // ← no cleanup if component unmounts before 100ms
  return () => window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
}, []);
```

Fix:

```tsx
useEffect(() => {
  const handleResize = () => setDimensions({ width: window.innerWidth, height: window.innerHeight });
  window.addEventListener('resize', handleResize);
  handleResize();
  const t = setTimeout(handleResize, 100);
  return () => {
    window.removeEventListener('resize', handleResize);
    clearTimeout(t);
  };
}, []);
```

---

**`StadiumCanvas.tsx` — `bgAudioRef` not paused on unmount**

The background defeat audio (`bgAudioRef`) is never paused in a cleanup. If `StadiumCanvas` unmounts mid-playback, audio continues indefinitely:

```tsx
// Add to the existing useEffect or a dedicated one:
return () => {
  if (bgAudioRef.current) bgAudioRef.current.pause();
};
```

